<h1><b><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:Arial;color:black;font-weight:bold'>Geithner's Rise Clouds =
Bair's
Prospects </span></font></b><o:p></o:p></h1>

<h3 style=3D'line-height:200%'><font size=3D1 color=3Dblack =
face=3DHelvetica><span
lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;line-height:200%;font-family:Helvetica;
color:black'>By </span></font><font size=3D1 color=3D"#666666" =
face=3DHelvetica><span
lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;line-height:200%;font-family:Helvetica;
color:#666666'><a
href=3D"http://online.wsj.com/search/search_center.html?KEYWORDS=3DDAMIAN=
+PALETTA&amp;ARTICLESEARCHQUERY_PARSER=3DbylineAND"><font
color=3Dblack><span =
style=3D'color:black;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:
.75pt;text-decoration:none'>DAMIAN =
PALETTA</span></font></a></span></font><o:p></o:p></h3>

<p style=3D'background:white'><st1:State w:st=3D"on"><st1:place =
w:st=3D"on"><font
  size=3D2 color=3Dblack face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;
  =
font-family:Arial;color:black'>WASHINGTON</span></font></st1:place></st1:=
State><font
size=3D2 color=3Dblack face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Arial;color:black'> -- Timothy Geithner's nomination as Treasury =
secretary
clouds the political future of Sheila Bair, the high-profile bank =
regulator who
has clashed occasionally with Mr. Geithner over the best way to =
stabilize the
banking sector.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>The most recent =
run-in
came this weekend, when the government scrambled to prevent the collapse =
of <a
href=3D"http://online.wsj.com/public/quotes/main.html?type=3Ddjn&amp;symb=
ol=3Dc"><font
color=3Dblack><span style=3D'color:black'>Citigroup</span></font></a> =
Inc. Mr.
Geithner helped lead talks that eventually set up a process for the =
government
to backstop a $306 billion portfolio of assets at Citigroup. Ms. Bair =
pushed
back repeatedly during the talks after some government officials had =
suggested
her agency, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., offer the brunt of the
government's guarantee, people familiar with the deliberations =
said.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=3Dtargetcaption style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 =
color=3Dblack
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Timothy
Geithner</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Although it =
isn't clear
which policy Mr. Geithner was advocating, he sought to steer the talks =
to a
rapid conclusion, despite Ms. Bair's objections, emphasizing that a =
quick
resolution was the most important concern. Eventually, government =
officials
hashed out a compromise that limited the FDIC's exposure, but only after =
the
emotional debates stretched late into Sunday =
evening.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>The episode was
illustrative of how two of the country's most powerful regulators have
addressed the banking crisis from different perspectives. They have, on =
more
than one occasion, tangled over how much her agency should shoulder the =
burden
of backstopping problems in the banking =
system.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>As head of the =
Federal
Reserve Bank of <st1:State w:st=3D"on"><st1:place w:st=3D"on">New =
York</st1:place></st1:State>,
Mr. Geithner is the Fed's eyes and ears on Wall Street. As Barack =
Obama's
Treasury secretary, he would have even broader powers and play an =
instrumental
role in redesigning the fractured <st1:country-region =
w:st=3D"on"><st1:place
 w:st=3D"on">U.S.</st1:place></st1:country-region> regulatory =
system.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Ms. Bair's =
agency has
wide powers, but she has resisted calls by the Fed and Treasury to =
broaden the FDIC's
exposure to troubled parts of the banking system -- changes she fears =
could
cost her agency billions of dollars. The FDIC is best known for its role
covering deposits at some 8,500 banks and thrifts. Ms. Bair has =
expressed
concern that expanding its responsibilities might lead to new costs on =
insured
banks, which fund the government insurance plan with =
fees.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=3Dtargetcaption style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 =
color=3Dblack
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Sheila
Bair</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Both Ms. Bair =
and Mr.
Geithner are hard-charging personalities who convey a calm public =
persona, yet
can be assertive and intense during =
negotiations.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>If confirmed as =
head of
Treasury, Mr. Geithner could have a big say over whether Ms. Bair, a
Republican, is asked to continue at the FDIC, take on another role in =
the
administration, or leave altogether. Ms. Bair, whose term ends in 2011, =
told
reporters Tuesday that she is &quot;quite content&quot; at the FDIC and =
would
&quot;work with the new administration in whatever role they want =
me.&quot;</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>But people =
close to Ms.
Bair said she would only stay at the agency if she felt she was wanted =
there
and wouldn't stand in the way of letting the new administration craft =
its own
team. Still, pushing her out would be politically risky. Ms. Bair is =
well-liked
by many on Capitol Hill -- both Democrats and Republicans -- who view =
her as
one of the government's most proactive officials when it comes to =
preventing
foreclosures. She also has won over consumer groups and community =
bankers,
which could make her politically untouchable. But her repeated clashes =
with the
Treasury and occasionally with top Fed officials have led to criticism =
that she
is difficult to negotiate with.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Mr. Geithner, =
through a
spokesman at the New York Fed, declined to =
comment.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Officials from =
the Obama
administration's transition team have met with FDIC officials to review =
the
agency's operations, but they haven't made any public statements about =
Ms.
Bair's eventual role. Her agency is facing a difficult stretch, and she =
said
Tuesday that there now are 171 banks and thrifts on the FDIC's
&quot;problem&quot; list, which means they are at a greater risk of =
failing. That
is up from 117 firms at the end of the second =
quarter.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Their dispute =
over
Citigroup came roughly a month after Ms. Bair and Mr. Geithner clashed =
over the
size and scope of a new and controversial program that uses the FDIC to
guarantee certain new debt issued by banks through June 2009. Mr. =
Geithner,
along with Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson and Fed Chairman Ben =
Bernanke,
wanted the debt guarantee to be broader, people familiar with the matter =
said,
as they felt this was necessary to restore confidence in =
<st1:country-region
w:st=3D"on"><st1:place w:st=3D"on">U.S.</st1:place></st1:country-region> =
banks. Ms.
Bair sought a more limited guarantee and questioned whether it was legal =
for
her agency to guarantee debt issued by bank parent =
companies.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>As with the =
Citigroup
debate, government officials eventually reached a compromise scaling =
back the
level of guarantees sought by the other =
regulators.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p style=3D'background:white'><font size=3D2 color=3Dblack =
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>Mr. Geithner =
and Ms.
Bair also clashed over whether regulators should block <a
href=3D"http://online.wsj.com/public/quotes/main.html?type=3Ddjn&amp;symb=
ol=3Dwfc"><font
color=3Dblack><span style=3D'color:black'>Wells Fargo</span></font></a> =
&amp; Co.'s
bid to acquire Wachovia Corp. shortly after the government had offered
Citigroup financial backing to do the deal, according to people involved =
in the
process.</span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'background:white'><cite><font size=3D2 =
color=3Dblack
face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;color:black'>&#8212;Jon
Hilsenrath contributed to this article.</span></font></cite><font =
size=3D2
color=3Dblack face=3DArial><span lang=3DEN =
style=3D'font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;
color:black'> </span></font><o:p></o:p></p>

